        body: "Every request flowing through Google's RPC framework carries one of four criticality values, and it's that value — not simply how busy the sender happens to be — that decides who gets sacrificed first once a backend or a customer's quota starts running short. CRITICAL_PLUS is reserved for requests where failure causes serious, unambiguous user-visible harm. CRITICAL is the default for ordinary production traffic: still meaningfully user-visible if it fails, but less catastrophic than CRITICAL_PLUS, and services are expected to provision enough capacity to fully cover both of these tiers under normal conditions. SHEDDABLE_PLUS is the default for batch work that can simply be retried minutes or hours later, where some partial unavailability is already an accepted cost of doing business. SHEDDABLE traffic is expected to see frequent partial and occasional full unavailability without anyone being surprised. Criticality is deliberately independent of latency requirements — a search-suggestions request that appears as someone types is highly sheddable, perfectly fine to simply not show under load, yet still needs to come back quickly on the occasions it is served, so the two axes are tracked separately rather than assumed to move together. Criticality also propagates automatically down a call tree: a backend handling a CRITICAL request that in turn issues its own outgoing requests passes that same CRITICAL label along by default, which is what lets a deeply nested dependency shed load in a way that stays consistent with the priority set all the way up at the original request, rather than each layer inventing its own local notion of what matters.",
