        body: "Retrying a failed request makes sense when a single backend task happens to be having a bad moment, but that logic stops holding once a meaningful slice of a whole datacenter is actually overloaded, because every retry just adds more load to the same overloaded pool it's trying to route around. The distinction that matters is scope: if only a small subset of backend tasks are struggling, an immediate retry is likely to land somewhere healthy and succeed; if a large subset of the datacenter is overloaded, retrying only compounds the problem, and the failure should be allowed to propagate straight back to the original caller instead of being quietly retried. Two separate budgets keep retries themselves from spiraling: a per-request budget caps any single logical request at a small, fixed number of attempts — three is a common choice — before giving up rather than trying forever, and a separate per-client budget tracks what fraction of a client's overall outgoing traffic consists of retries, refusing to retry at all once that fraction crosses roughly ten percent, since a client retrying more than that is itself evidence that more than one unlucky task is involved. A related discipline applies to deep call stacks: only the layer sitting immediately above whichever component is doing the rejecting should retry, not every layer above it independently, because retry rates compound multiplicatively as they climb a stack — a handful of retries permitted at each of several layered services can turn a single user action into dozens of attempts hitting the lowest layer, which is exactly the wrong direction to push a component that's already struggling.",
