        title: "What NALSD Is, and Why 'Non-Abstract' Is the Point",
        body: "Non-Abstract Large System Design, or NALSD, is an iterative methodology for turning a rough system sketch into a concrete, defensible resource proposal, blending capacity planning, deliberate component isolation, and graceful degradation into a single repeatable design habit. The 'non-abstract' half of the name is the whole point: every system eventually has to run on real machines, in real datacenters, over real networks with real physical limits, so the discipline of continually converting an abstract whiteboard idea into actual figures — how many machines, how much memory, how much network bandwidth — is what surfaces a fatal physical constraint while it's still cheap to fix, rather than discovering it after the design is already built. The exercise deliberately drives toward concrete numbers, but the numbers themselves aren't really the point; the value lies in practicing sound, explicit assumptions and being able to defend them, since even imperfect assumptions, combined across several iterations, build a far better understanding of a design's actual shape than staying comfortably abstract ever would. It's a skill SREs are expected to exercise routinely — starting from a basic sketch of a system, reasoning through how it would need to scale and where it could fail, and arriving at a concrete resource estimate — precisely because production systems keep changing shape, and that reasoning muscle atrophies if it's only exercised once at initial design time.",
